"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938696","Home Office","false","2018-07-16","<p>As set out in paragraph 6.12 of the Statement of Intent on the EU Settlement Scheme published on 21 June 2018, provision in the Immigration Rules will be made for a non-EU citizen who is the primary carer of a British citizen in the UK and who currently derives a right of residence from wider EU law (a Zambrano carer). Further details will be provided in due course on the new status which will be available to them.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-07-16T15:38:49.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938696/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938696/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-11","Immigration: Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans he has to bring forward proposals on the status of Zambrano carers after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","163111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938697","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-16","<p>In 2017 from non-EU countries, the UK imported approximately:</p><p> </p><ul><li>£4 billion of ‘plants which are food’, weighing 3.7 million tonnes.</li><li>£4 billion of ‘meat and animal products’, weighing 1 million tonnes.</li><li>£6 billion of ‘other food products’, weighing 7.1 million tonnes.</li></ul><p> </p><p>Ports keep records of all consignments of imported food of animal origin and high-risk food not of animal origin (food not of animal origin subject to EU sampling legislation) on the TRACES computer system. Other government bodies such as HMRC also keep some records of food imports.</p><p> </p><p>It should be noted that HMRC only collect details of imports of goods at specific points of entry from non-EU countries – currently the same data is not collected for movements of goods from EU member states at specific points of entry.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-07-16T14:35:17.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938697/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938697/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-07-11","Food and Plants: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate his Department has made of the (a) value and (b) volume of (i) plant material, (ii) meat or animal material and (iii) other food products imported at each point of entry into the UK; and what records of those imports are make at each point of entry.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","163122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938698","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-16","<p>Defra has an extensive programme of work focused on preparing for a range of scenarios to make sure we are ready for the point when the UK leaves the EU. Ministers and officials regularly liaise with colleagues across Government including with HMRC. This includes discussions on the UK’s systems for the management of trade in animal and plant materials. The precise nature of our future relationship with the EU is still to be determined and is the subject of negotiation.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-07-16T12:30:53.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938698/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938698/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-07-11","Animals and Plants: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions he has had with HMRC on the capacity of its customs computer system for plant and animal imports to process potential increased volumes of applications after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","163123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938699","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-20","<p>Departmental officials are aware that there were some short term supply issues which affected the availability of olanzapine and quetiapine tablets in May/June 2017.</p><p> </p><p>A major generic supplier of olanzapine tablets experienced some short term manufacturing issues which consequently meant other suppliers experienced an increase in demand at short notice, which they could not readily meet. However, the manufacturing issues were resolved quickly and the overall supply of olanzapine tablets improved within a few weeks.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of quetiapine supply issues, this was caused by a major generic supplier, with large market shares of quetiapine tablets, discontinuing this product range without notifying the Department. This led to significant market disruption as other suppliers experienced a large increase in demand at short notice. However, suppliers were able to bring in additional supplies to cope with the extra demand and supplies improved by July 2017.</p><p> </p><p>During this period, Departmental officials were in regular contact with all United Kingdom licensed suppliers of both quetiapine and olanzapine and worked closely with them to discuss their supply position and to ensure sufficient suppliers remained available to meet UK requirements.</p><p> </p><p>We are not aware of any current supply issues affecting olanzapine and quetiapine and several suppliers have confirmed that supplies are readily available.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","162969 ; 163503","2018-07-20T09:38:48.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938699/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938699/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-07-11","Olanzapine and Quetiapine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to help ensure the supply of (a) olanzapine and (b) quetiapine meets demand for those drugs.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","162968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938700","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-20","<p>Departmental officials are aware that there were some short term supply issues which affected the availability of olanzapine and quetiapine tablets in May/June 2017.</p><p> </p><p>A major generic supplier of olanzapine tablets experienced some short term manufacturing issues which consequently meant other suppliers experienced an increase in demand at short notice, which they could not readily meet. However, the manufacturing issues were resolved quickly and the overall supply of olanzapine tablets improved within a few weeks.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of quetiapine supply issues, this was caused by a major generic supplier, with large market shares of quetiapine tablets, discontinuing this product range without notifying the Department. This led to significant market disruption as other suppliers experienced a large increase in demand at short notice. However, suppliers were able to bring in additional supplies to cope with the extra demand and supplies improved by July 2017.</p><p> </p><p>During this period, Departmental officials were in regular contact with all United Kingdom licensed suppliers of both quetiapine and olanzapine and worked closely with them to discuss their supply position and to ensure sufficient suppliers remained available to meet UK requirements.</p><p> </p><p>We are not aware of any current supply issues affecting olanzapine and quetiapine and several suppliers have confirmed that supplies are readily available.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","162968 ; 163503","2018-07-20T09:38:48.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938700/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938700/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-07-11","Olanzapine and Quetiapine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what representations his Department has made to manufacturers of (a) olanzapine and (b) quetiapine on the supply of those drugs since 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","162969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938701","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-17","<p>I have asked Sir John Kingman to carry out the review independently. Summaries of the discussions of the Review’s Advisory Group will be available at the gov.uk website.</p><p> </p><p>The final report will also include details of all the organisations consulted in the course of the review.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-07-17T16:59:44.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938701/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938701/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938701/answer/previousversion/69820","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-07-11","Financial Reporting Council Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the terms of reference of the Independent Review of the Financial Reporting Council 2018, if he will publish summary meeting notes for all meetings of that review.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","163124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938702","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-16","<p>The written evidence submitted by the Department to the High Court in respect of this judicial review is already available to all the parties concerned – that is the Court, the Claimant, and the Interested Parties – and this matter is currently before the Court. I will arrange for a copy of the evidence to be placed in the Library of the House following the Court’s determination of this matter</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-07-16T14:08:01.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938702/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938702/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-11","Judicial Review: Christchurch Borough Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will place in the Library a copy of the written evidence submitted by his Department to the High Court in respect of the judicial review being brought by Christchurch Borough Council scheduled for a hearing on 30 July 2018.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Sir Christopher Chope","162972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938703","Department for Education","false","2018-07-19","<p>This is a matter for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Amanda Spielman. I have asked her to write to the hon. Member and a copy of her reply will be placed in the Libraries of both Houses.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","163167 ; 163168 ; 163169","2018-07-19T17:15:46.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938703/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938703/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-07-11","Pre-school Education: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many private nursery schools were rated (a) Good and (b) Outstanding at their last Ofsted inspection.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","163170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938704","Department for Education","false","2018-07-24","<p>The Department trusts schools to manage their own budgets. The vast majority of schools are operating with a cumulative surplus, with only a small percentage in cumulative deficit. An academy trust may contain a mixture of primary and secondary academies. Trusts are the legal entities responsible for academies, including their finances and are accountable at trust level.</p><p>The most recent figures show that 9% of maintained schools are in cumulative deficit, compared to 6% of academy trusts. The proportion of all schools in cumulative deficit or in trusts with a cumulative deficit was lower in 2017 than it was in 2010 (7.6% versus 9.1%). Published data for 2010 covers local authority maintained schools only, reflecting the fact that almost all schools were local authority maintained at this point.</p><p>The table shows the proportion of maintained schools and academy trusts with a cumulative deficit each year from 2014/15 to 2016/17, the latest year for which data is available:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Percentage of maintained schools and trusts in cumulative deficit</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>All maintained schools </strong>(including special and PRU schools)</p></td><td><p>5.4%</p></td><td><p>6.0%</p></td><td><p><strong>9.1%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nursery maintained schools</p></td><td><p>10.6%</p></td><td><p>12.7%</p></td><td><p>18.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Primary maintained schools</p></td><td><p>4.2%</p></td><td><p>4.5%</p></td><td><p>7.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Secondary maintained schools</p></td><td><p>15.0%</p></td><td><p>17.8%</p></td><td><p>26.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Academy trusts</strong></p></td><td><p>4.0%</p></td><td><p>5.5%</p></td><td><p><strong>6.1%</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Percentage of schools in cumulative deficit or in trusts with a cumulative deficit</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All schools</p></td><td><p>9.1%</p></td><td><p>7.6%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-07-24T15:21:42.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938704/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938704/answer","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938704/answer/previousversion/69316",,"60","Education","Education","2018-07-11","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of (a) maintained nursery schools, (b) local authority maintained primary schools, (c) maintained secondary schools, (d) primary academies and (e) secondary academy schools were in budget deficit in (i) the last and (ii) each of the preceding three financial years.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","163116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938705","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-16","<p>The features that have been identified for protection at Selsey Bill and the Hounds are:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li><p>Bracklesham Bay geological feature</p></li><li><p>Short-snouted seahorse</p></li><li><p>Subtidal mixed sediments</p></li><li><p>Subtidal sand</p></li><li><p>Peat and clay exposures</p></li><li><p>High energy infralittoral rock</p></li><li><p>Moderate energy infralittoral rock</p></li><li><p>Moderate energy circalittoral rock</p></li><li><p>Low energy infralittoral rock</p><p> </p><p>Full details regarding the proposed designation of Selsey Bill and the Hounds can be found in the Third Tranche of Marine Conservation Zones consultation. Please see link here:</p><p><a href="https://consult.defra.gov.uk/marine/consultation-on-the-third-tranche-of-marine-conser/" target="_blank">https://consult.defra.gov.uk/marine/consultation-on-the-third-tranche-of-marine-conser/</a>.</p></li></ul><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-07-16T13:54:03.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938705/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938705/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-07-11","Marine Conservation Zones: West Sussex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which marine life and seabed habitats have been identified for protection in the proposed marine conservation zone at Selsey Bill and the Hounds.","false","Biography information for Gillian Keegan","Chichester","Gillian Keegan","163226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938706","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-16","<p>Before making any new secondary legislation we intend to invite comments on those preliminary views from the shadow authorities for the areas concerned, which will be responsible for setting the 2019-20 council taxes – in the case of Dorset from the Shadow Dorset Council, the members of which include the members of East Dorset District Council, and from the Shadow Bournemouth, Christchurch, and Poole Council, the members of which include the members of Christchurch Borough Council.</p><p> </p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-07-16T14:27:10.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938706/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938706/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-11","Council Tax: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what consultations he is undertaking with (a) Christchurch Borough Council and (b) East Dorset District Council on the content of potential draft secondary legislation on future harmonisation of council taxes in Dorset.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Sir Christopher Chope","162973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938707","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-07-19","<p>Pursuant to my previous answer, the £9,781,587 figure referred to was correctly spent by NCS providers in advance of delivery of the programme. This amount contributed to the upfront costs that are shared with providers to set up the programme for a specified number of places. Unfortunately, some of these places were not filled, and the advance payments for unfilled places cannot be recovered.</p><p> </p><p>Reducing the number of unfilled places is a priority for DCMS in order to deliver better value for money. We have reflected this in the NCS Trust’s performance framework and NCS Trust are improving their commissioning model to allow participation volumes to flex throughout the year in response to demand and reduce the number of unfilled places.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-07-19T09:13:01.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938707/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938707/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938707/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-07-11","National Citizen Service Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 23 April 2018 to Question 135849 on National Citizen Service Trust, whether around £9,781,587 has been written off by the Government for places that were not filled in 2016 for the National Citizen Service.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","163141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938708","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-18","<p>The Government has always been clear that shale gas development must be safe and environmentally sound. We are committed to ensuring a rigorous, evidence-based approach to shale gas extraction, and as such I welcome any new research that can further enhance our understanding and help inform our policy development.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-07-18T10:42:04.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938708/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938708/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938708/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-07-11","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will take account of the Royal Society's update of its report of June 2012 on shale gas extraction before continuing his plans to extract such gas.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","163047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938709","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-07-19","<p>DCMS does permit NCS delivery partners to profit from their service delivery contracts. However, driving down costs is a priority for the Department and we are working with NCS Trust to ensure value for money for the taxpayer. While, direct comparisons are not straightforward due to the unique nature of NCS, a recent independent benchmarking exercise, commissioned by the Department, indicates that the programme compares favourably to the costs of other similar programmes in the sector, and internationally.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-07-19T09:14:36.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938709/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938709/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-07-11","National Citizen Service Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 23 April 2018 to Question 135849, whether a delivery partner of the National Citizen Service programme is permitted to profit from their service delivery contracts.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","163142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938710","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-07-16","<p>We are currently in discussion with representatives of the Dorset councils about the content of secondary legislation to support implementation of the local government reorganisation on 1 April 2019 for which Parliament has legislated, and intend to lay the necessary secondary legislation as soon as practicable.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-07-16T14:19:23.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938710/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938710/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-07-11","Local Government: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what the timetable is for the Government's publication of draft secondary legislation on local government reorganisation in Dorset; and what account the Government is taking of the consequences for that timetable of the timing of the hearing on 30 July 2018 of the judicial review application being brought by Christchurch Borough Council on local government reorganisation in Dorset.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Sir Christopher Chope","162974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938711","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-16","<p>​We are aware of reports of attacks against Christians in Tamil Nadu. We condemn any instances of discrimination because of religion or belief, regardless of the country or faith involved. In support of minorities, the British High Commission in New Delhi, our network of Deputy High Commissions, as well as Foreign and Commonwealth Office officials in London, maintain a continuous assessment of the human rights situation across India.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-07-16T15:38:48.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938711/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938711/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938711/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-07-11","India: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of recent attacks upon Christians in the Indian state of Tamil Nadu.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","162977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938712","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-07-18","<p>A collection of registers of Birth, Deaths and Marriages for the Chagos Archipelago between 1884 and 1971 is currently held in the FCO Archives. We will consider what future actions may be most suitable for these registers as part of our ongoing programme of records appraisal. This will include consideration of the status of the registers and where they will ultimately be deposited.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-07-18T14:53:08.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938712/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938712/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938712/answer","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938712/answer/previousversion/69833","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-07-11","British Indian Ocean Territory: Ilois","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will deposit in the National Archives the Registers of Births, Deaths and Marriages for the Chagos Archipelago between 1884 and 1971.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","163140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938713","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-07-19","<p>The National Citizen Service Trust is collaborating with the Parliament Education Service to deliver workshops to young people during Summer 2018 which focus on how Parliament works and how young people can take action on the issues that matter to them. The NCS curriculum currently includes informing young people about the importance of the democratic process and when the NCS Trust Royal Charter body launches it will be mandated to promote democratic engagement.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-07-19T09:16:10.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938713/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938713/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938713/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-07-11","National Citizen Service Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether the National Citizen Service Trust has plans to collaborate with the Parliament Education Service in the summer of 2018 to increase citizenship and democratic engagement.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","163143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938714","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-07-16","<p>The legal aid scheme is monitored by the number of cases funded, as opposed to the number of people who have been in receipt of that funding. This is because one individual may receive legal aid on multiple occasions.</p><p> </p><p>A secured statutory charge exists in favour of the Legal Aid Agency in 24,880 cases as at 31<sup>st</sup> March 2018.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-07-16T13:26:14.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938714/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938714/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/938714/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-07-11","Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice,  how many people have an outstanding statutory charge placed by the Legal Aid Agency against their property.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","162954"
