"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937759","Scotland Office","false","2018-07-16","<p>I have frequent discussions with Cabinet colleagues covering all sectors of the economy, constructively feeding into the regular talks this Government has been having with the EU on the future framework, outlining our positions on a wide range of topics covering the future security partnership and the future economic partnership.</p><p> </p><p>We are working on delivering for Scotland across the board. On agriculture, food, and farming, the Agriculture Bill will deliver on our manifesto commitment to provide stability for farmers as we exit the EU. On manufacturing and construction, we are determined to ensure that the UK continues to be one of the most competitive locations in the world. On Financial Services, we will be seeking a bold and ambitious free trade agreement of greater scope and ambition than any such agreement before it, so that it covers sectors crucial to our linked economies. On life sciences, we are seeking a comprehensive system of mutual recognition to ensure that, as now, pharmaceutical products and medical devices only need to undergo one series of approvals in one country.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","162625 ; 162626 ; 162627","2018-07-16T12:04:48.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937759/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937759/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937759/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-07-10","Life Sciences: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on the support available to Scotland’s life sciences sector to ensure that all business transactions and procedures remain consistent after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Lesley Laird","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Lesley Laird","162628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937760","Scotland Office","false","2018-07-16","<p>I commend the work undertaken by foodbanks across the UK. I meet with stakeholders to discuss a wide range of issues including food poverty in Scotland.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-07-16T12:20:34.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937760/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937760/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937760/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-07-10","Food Banks: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether he has discussions with food bank service providers in Scotland in the last twelve months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lesley Laird","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Lesley Laird","162629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937761","Scotland Office","false","2018-07-16","I speak with the Secretary of State for International Trade regularly on a range of issues. Existing EU regulations mean that some skin and fur products may never be legally imported into the UK for commercial use. These include cat and dog fur and products as well as seal skins and products from commercial hunts. Regulations banning the import of these furs will remain in force after the UK has left the EU, as these will be converted into UK domestic law through the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill. ","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2018-07-16T12:17:34.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937761/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937761/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937761/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-07-10","Furs: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether he has had discussions with the Secretary of State for International Trade on extending existing fur import bans to cover all species exploited by the fur trade; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lesley Laird","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Lesley Laird","162630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937762","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-07-16","<p>Our Industrial Strategy recognises the role of new markets like space launch in driving growth across the UK. The Government is delivering a major programme to enable companies to offer small satellite launch and sub-orbital spaceflight from UK spaceports.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Space Agency has considered 26 proposals for grant funding to kick-start satellite launch and spaceflight operations in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>On Monday we announced £31.5 million in funding to enable satellites to be launched from Sutherland, Scotland, which aims to be the first vertical spaceport to launch satellites into space from mainland Europe.</p><p> </p><p>Alongside this, we have also announced plans, subject to business case, for up to £2 million of funding for airports such as Newquay, Glasgow Prestwick and Snowdonia planning to build the market for horizontal spaceflight using air-launched rockets and sub-orbital spaceplanes.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-07-16T15:43:31.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937762/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937762/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937762/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-07-10","Spaceflight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent progress his Department has made being made on establishing a site for a UK space launch facility.","false","Biography information for Jamie Stone","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Jamie Stone","162607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937763","Home Office","false","2018-07-16","<p>The Home Office awarded £900,000 in Special Grant funding to the Sussex Police and Crime Commissioner in 2014/15, and £1.4 million in Special Grant funding to the Lancashire Police and Crime Commissioner in 2017/18, for the costs of policing anti-fracking protests.</p><p>The Home Office carefully considers requests for additional funding through Special Grant.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-07-16T16:24:41.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937763/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937763/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937763/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-07-10","Fracking: Protest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what additional funding his Department has allocated to local police forces for the policing of fracking sites.","false","Biography information for Alex Norris","Nottingham North","Alex Norris","162620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937764","Prime Minister","false","2018-07-18","<p>On appointment to each new office, Ministers provide a list of all relevant interests to their Permanent Secretary, which are considered by the Cabinet Office, and the Prime Minister’s Independent Adviser on Ministers’ Interests. The next list of Ministers' relevant interests will be published in due course.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2018-07-18T15:39:18.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937764/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937764/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937764/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2018-07-10","Attorney General: Members' Interests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, when she plans to publish the declaration of interest of the new Attorney General.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","162502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937765","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-16","<p>In May the Government announced £40 million over the next five years for brain tumour research as part of the Dame Tessa Jowell Brain Cancer Mission.</p><p> </p><p>Funding will be invested through the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) to support a wide range of research from early translation (experimental medicine) through clinical and on to applied research. We are relying on researchers to submit high-quality research proposals in this difficult area. To encourage such applications we have released an NIHR Highlight Notice on brain tumour research calling for proposals across a range of NIHR research funding programmes.</p><p> </p><p>Total spend over the last five years is shown in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£3,417,427</p></td><td><p>£4,271,133</p></td><td><p>£3,699,965</p></td><td><p>£3,151,001</p></td><td><p>£3,966,299</p></td><td><p>£18,505,826</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","162479","2018-07-16T11:28:49.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937765/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937765/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-07-10","Brain: Tumours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much funding his Department plans to allocate to brain tumour research in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","162478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937766","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-16","<p>In May the Government announced £40 million over the next five years for brain tumour research as part of the Dame Tessa Jowell Brain Cancer Mission.</p><p> </p><p>Funding will be invested through the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) to support a wide range of research from early translation (experimental medicine) through clinical and on to applied research. We are relying on researchers to submit high-quality research proposals in this difficult area. To encourage such applications we have released an NIHR Highlight Notice on brain tumour research calling for proposals across a range of NIHR research funding programmes.</p><p> </p><p>Total spend over the last five years is shown in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£3,417,427</p></td><td><p>£4,271,133</p></td><td><p>£3,699,965</p></td><td><p>£3,151,001</p></td><td><p>£3,966,299</p></td><td><p>£18,505,826</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","162478","2018-07-16T11:28:49.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937766/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937766/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937766/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-07-10","Brain: Tumours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much funding his Department has allocated to brain tumour research in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","162479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937767","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-16","<p>Discussions between Natural England and the trails partnerships on their future funding settlements are ongoing. These discussions are in the context of the Natural Environment and Rural Communities Act Committee’s recommendation to move towards a more sustainable funding model in the long term whilst maintaining a high quality experience for the user.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-07-16T11:40:55.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937767/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937767/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937767/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-07-10","Public Footpaths","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has to continue funding National Trails beyond the current financial year.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","162491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937768","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-16","<p>Significant portions of existing national trails fall within boundaries of existing national parks and areas of outstanding natural beauty. These important assets can expect to receive attention through the Glover Review, which will enable all stakeholders to express their views on the future of these places.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-07-16T11:52:54.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937768/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937768/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937768/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-07-10","Public Footpaths","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of including National Trails in the ongoing review of National Parks and Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","162492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937769","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-16","<p>Since 2013 the promotion of national trails and the ‘acorn’ (registered trademark) has been carried out by Walk Unlimited, a social enterprise, which champions the network through its website www.nationaltrail.co.uk. It works with the individual trail partnerships who remain responsible for providing information on their trail to the national site and for local promotion. Natural England also encourages individual trail partnerships and the emerging England Coast Path partners to consider promotion of both the individual trails and stretches of those trails and the promotion of the family of national trails.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-07-16T11:56:57.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937769/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937769/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937769/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-07-10","Public Footpaths","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to promote use of National Trails.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","162493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937770","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-07-16","<p>The most recent estimate from 2013 is that at least 70 million visits are made each year to places passed through by a national trail.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-07-16T12:12:31.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937770/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937770/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937770/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-07-10","Public Footpaths","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the number of people who use National Trails every year.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","162494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937771","Department for Education","false","2018-07-16","<p>The School Teachers’ Review Body (STRB) which makes recommendations on the 2018 pay award, has recently submitted its 28th Report to my right hon. Friend, the Secretary of State. The Government is carefully considering the report from the STRB and its recommendations. The Department will publish the report and the response as soon as possible.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-07-16T13:00:38.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937771/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937771/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937771/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-07-10","School Teachers' Review Body","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the timetable is for the next School Teachers’ Review Body report to be published.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","162549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937772","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-07-17","<p>Public Health England (PHE) has been funded by cancer charities to pilot and assess the feasibility of an ovarian cancer audit, this pilot will take place over the next two years.</p><p> </p><p>Since early diagnosis increases survival outcomes, NHS England is working to diagnose cancer earlier and faster. This is particularly important for cancers like ovarian, where early diagnosis makes a huge difference in survival. We are developing new models of care and pathways that will transform services by speeding up diagnosis. This includes the commitment to roll out a new Faster Diagnosis Standard by 2020 to ensure that patients referred for an investigation with a suspicion of cancer are diagnosed or have cancer ruled out within 28 days.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has also committed more than £200 million in cancer services between 2017 and 2019, to accelerate diagnosis, improve survival and enhance quality of life.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is introducing Rapid Diagnostic and Assessment Centres which will operate as one-stop shops to reduce time-to diagnosis and time-to-first treatment. This is a real step change in the way people with unclear symptoms are identified, diagnosed and treated. General practitioners can refer patients suffering from vague symptoms.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is also delivering the largest single upgrade in National Health Service cancer treatment for the last 15 years. The £130 million radiotherapy modernisation programme is upgrading and replacing radiotherapy equipment in hospitals across England. Through this programme, patients will have access to the most modern, innovative radiotherapy techniques to create better health outcomes and improve patient experience.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is also closely working with PHE to develop an approach to raise awareness of generic symptoms that can indicate a wider number of cancers, including ovarian cancer, and the need to visit the doctor promptly with these symptoms.</p><p> </p><p>PHE also ran a regional pilot ovarian campaign in the North West of England from 10 February to 16 March 2014. The campaign’s key message was ‘Feeling bloated, most days, for three weeks or more could be a sign of ovarian cancer. Tell your doctor’.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","162543 ; 162544","2018-07-17T15:05:38.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937772/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937772/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/937772/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-07-10","Ovarian Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he has plans to authorise a national clinical audit of ovarian cancer; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","162542"
